text: When I first heard about this I was excited however also saddened. I know there were seven books on Mary Poppins and I can easily understand why they wanted to make a sequel.. but for me - personally - it won't be the same without Julie Andrews. What she gave to the role was something magical that'll remain close to mine - and other peoples - hearts forever. I can't express how much the film meant to me and does. Of course they needed to use another actress, as Julie is getting old now and has lost her wonderful singing voice. Although half of me wishes they would have left it all alone and just stuck with the first one I am also half excited to see what this film will bring. If anyone - other than Julie - was to play Mary Poppins, I am glad they picked Emily Blunt: she is a national treasure and her singing voice is lovely to hear: I am looking forward to what Emily has in store :)  Plus: Freaking out that Angela Lansbury will appear in this! :D

text: It must have been a real treat to have watched the original Mary Poppins, starring the incomparable Julie Andrews and her co-star Dick Van Dyke, in 1963. It was the first live-action animated feature from Disney, in colour. Probably most households in Britain still did not have a television in 1963. And if there was a television, it would have been a black-and-white. What matters is the characterisation in a movie more than anything else. It's the characterisation that gives a movie its particular charm. Mary Poppins the movie, so fun, colourful and imaginative, had a long run in cinemas in America. It was made in America; the great songs in it were conceived in America; the movie was extremely popular: it captured the imagination!!!!  America gets a bad rap in the press every week these days. Seemingly Americans do. But without America and the American spirit, the world, the young, middle-aged and elderly, would scarcely be charmed or entertained at all. Could Mary Poppins the movie have sprung from somewhere else? Perhaps Britain (the author was Australian/British). The reality is the movie itself could not have sprung from anywhere else, in the 60s, not even from Canada next door let alone from anywhere in another continent. The world needs this kind of entertainment. Obviously the world still looks to America. When the channels were few, entertainment was dominating the airwaves. Now there's too much crass, nasty stuff going on in the world. I hope the sequel enthrals audiences as much as the original from 55 years ago!

text: I don't suppose Disney could just leave well enough alone for once? I get it, creativity is hard and some good movies truly do deserve sequels, but really? First Pirates of the Caribbean with two movies too many, then Star Wars, and now Mary Poppins. Some stories should just end at a certain place and time, and to drag them out any longer would just cheapen and ruin them. Mary Poppins is one of those movies, and while perhaps it is unfair to judge a book by it's cover (or a movie by it's trailer, to be more accurate), Disney has a bad track record when it comes to judging these sorts of things. Anyone ever heard of the Law of Diminishing Marginal Utility? It's an economic principle that dictates that after a certain point more does not equal better, and that every additional unit of the good or service in question acquired has less value to the consumer than it's predecessors. This applies to movies and sequels too, but Disney doesn't seem to have caught on to that yet, and now Mary Poppins seems to be the next casualty in their neverending quest for profit by quantity and not quality.

You have some of the best writers and directors and support teams and staff ever assembled in the history of movie making and they can stand tall on their own feet.  Let your creators shine.  They have their own stories to tell the world.  If you devote so much time and resources to revisiting the past you will miss out on making the classics of the next generation. text: When I read some of these comments I say to myself what sad, unhappy individuals many of you homo-sapiens seem to be....some very nasty ones too!  Buy for myself, I can still remember my grand-mother taking me to see this film when I was all but 4-5 years old.  We did not have "Media on demand" at our fingertips back then or even cable TV, only Cinema (By Bus, Car or Foot) or TV (by an Antenna stuck on the roof). I can still recall my granddad with the ladder up on the roof, on top of one of the chimneys (we heated with coal, back then) trying to position the thing in order to get a good signal, on the tiny color TV. No big screen back then, or tablets.  Now, 50 plus years later, after watching this teaser and getting tiny little goosebumps, I will reserve judgement until I see the MOVIE!  It was that Kite..... text: The Mary Poppins of the book is nothing like the Mary Poppins of the film. She's a commoner, calling all birds 'sparrers' and spouting off other working class turns of phrase. The books are a bit Lewis Carrollesque in that the structure barely matters -The movie and the play are both unwatchable and the books are unreadable. She's a cruel, heartless, mean-spirited woman who threatens to call the police on kids for the heinous crime of not being sleepy, and when Disney tried to balance that out by giving her a sappy side, she just got watered down. Meanwhile, the songs in the movie are fucking annoying and have bad messages (sexism, encouraging kids to take sugar with medicine) and I can't believe one of them won an Oscar.     Then there was the battle between Walt Disney and author  (Saving Mr. Banks (2013)  financially strapped author Pamela "P. L." Travers reluctantly travels from her home in London to Los Angeles to work with Walt Disney at the urging of her agent, Diarmuid Russell. Disney has pursued the film rights to her Mary Poppins stories for twenty years, having promised his daughters that he would produce a film based on them. Travers has steadfastly resisted Disney's efforts because she fears what he would do to her character. However, she has not written anything in a while and her book royalties have dwindled to nothing, so she risks losing her house. Still, Russell has to remind her that Disney has agreed to two major stipulations‚Äîno animation and unprecedented script approval. Walt Disney lied to GTravers, stole her concept,  and then did not even have the decency to invite TRavers to the opening. Travers had to crash the party so to speak.
